{{Infobox language |name=Abanyom |altname=Bakor |states=[[Nigeria]] |region=[[Cross River State]] |speakers={{sigfig|12,500|2}} |date=1986 |ref=e19 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Ekoid languages|Ekoid]] |fam6=Efutop–Ekajuk |iso3=abm |glotto=aban1242 |glottorefname=Abanyom }}
'''Abanyom''', or '''Bakor''', is a language of the [[Ekoid languages|Ekoid]] subfamily of [[Niger–Congo languages|Niger–Congo]]. It is spoken by the Abanyom people in the [[Cross River State]] region of [[Nigeria]]. A member of the [[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] group, Abanyom is fairly closely related to the [[Bantu languages]]. It is [[tone (linguistics)|tonal]] and has a typical Niger–Congo [[noun class]] system.
==Sources== {{reflist}} *Asinya, O.E. 1987. A reconstruction of the Segmental phonology of Bakor (an Ekoid Bantu language). M.A. Linguistics, University of Port Harcourt
