{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Johann Heinrich Baumann | image = Johann Heinrich Baumann, self-portrait.jpg | caption = Johann Heinrich Baumann, self-portrait | pseudonym = | birth_date ={{Birth date|1753|02|09}} | birth_place = [[Jelgava|Mitau]], [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia]] | death_date ={{Death date and age|1832|07|29|1753|02|09}} | death_place = | occupation =Painter | nationality =[[Baltic German]] | period = [[Baroque]] | genre = | subject = Hunting scenes | movement = | spouse = | children = | relatives = | influences = [[Jacob Samuel Beck]] | influenced = | signature = | website = | alma_mater = University of Erfurt }}
'''Johann Heinrich Baumann''' ({{lang-lv|Johans Heinrihs Baumanis}}; 9 February 1753 – 29 July 1832) was a [[Baltic German]] artist who mainly lived and worked in what is today [[Latvia]].
==Early life and education== Johann Heinrich Baumann was born in [[Jelgava]] ({{lang-de|Mitau}}) into a German-speaking family. He was the son of the pastor and [[Superintendent (ecclesiastical)|general superintendent of Mitau]], Joachim Baumann.
==University== Baumann went to [[University of Erfurt]] to study theology in 1773–1776. However, in Erfurt he took up painting, under the influence of {{ill|Jacob Samuel Beck|de|Jakob Samuel Beck}} (1715–1778), a notable local painter specialising in animal portraits in the then-prevailing [[Baroque]] style. After his studies, Baumann returned to his Baltic homeland [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia|Courland]] but would henceforth pursue a career as an artist and not as a priest.<ref>{{cite book |last= Neumann|first= Wilhelm|authorlink= |title= Lexikon Baltischer Künstler|url= https://archive.org/stream/lexikonbaltisch00drgoog#page/n18/mode/2up|accessdate= 14 April 2013|year= 1908|publisher= Jonck & Poliewsky|language=German|location= Riga |page=7}}</ref><ref name=hunter>{{cite web |url= http://www.studija.lv/en/?parent=842|title= The Hunter with A Paintbrush|last1= Lamberga|first1= Dace|year= 2004 |publisher= Studija Visual Arts Magazine|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>
==Travels== Being a keen hunter, Baumann travelled as far as present-day [[Lithuania]], [[Russia]] and [[Belarus]] on hunting expeditions.<ref name=hunter/> He also wrote anecdotal, whimsical short stories about his hunting adventures, for which he has been called the "[[Baron Munchausen|Munchausen]] of [[Courland]]".<ref name=artoflativa/> His outdoors interests also came to dominate his art completely, which is an unusual blend of skillfulness and professionalism mixed with naivety and slovenliness. Almost all his known paintings depict animals, hunting scenes or related subjects.<ref name=hunter/> His style is perhaps best characterised as a provincial form of [[Baroque]], inspired to some extent by similar motives in [[Dutch Golden Age painting]], executed in a highly personal way. Although he never became recognised as a major artist in [[Russian Empire|Imperial Russia]], he was still acknowledged by a special mention of the [[Imperial Academy of Arts]] in 1786. He is reputed to have painted over 1700 paintings, however only 43 surviving paintings are safely attributed to him today.<ref name=hunter/><ref name=artoflativa>{{cite web |url= http://www.artoflatvia.lv/darbi/19|title= Johans Heinrihs Baumanis|last1= Belēvičs|first1= Guntis|publisher= Latvian Art Classics|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>
==Playwriting== Baumann was also one of the first authors in present-day [[Latvia]] to write plays for the stage in [[Latvian language|Latvian]].<ref name=hunter/>
==See also== * [[List of Baltic Germans#Artists|List of Baltic German artists]]
